WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Our scripture reading will be out of Ephesians 2, 1 through 10.

2
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
And you were dead in the trespasses and sins in which you once walked,

3
00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
following the course of this world, following the prince of the power of the air,

4
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
the spirit that is now at work in the sons of disobedience,

5
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
among whom we all once lived in the passions of our flesh,

6
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
carrying out the desires of the body and the mind.

7
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
And we're by nature children of wrath like the rest of mankind.

8
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
But God, being rich in mercy because of the great love with which he has loved us,

9
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
even when we were dead in our trespasses, made us alive together with Christ.

10
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
By grace you have been saved and raised up with him

11
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.000
and seated us with him in the heavenly places in Christ Jesus,

12
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
so that in the coming ages he might show the immeasurable riches of his grace

13
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and kindness towards us in Christ Jesus.

14
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
For by grace you have been saved through faith, and this is not of your own doing.

15
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
It is the gift of God, not a result of works so that no one may boast.

16
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
For we are his workmanship created in Christ Jesus for good works,

17
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
which God prepared beforehand that we should walk in them.

18
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
This is the word of the Lord.

19
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So we're going to be going through Ephesians chapter 2.

20
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
This morning we saw the first part of it last week,

21
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
and we're going to be going through the next little bit here.

22
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Just as we get started, I'll share a little story with you.

23
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Back in 1773 an Anglican minister in England sat down to write his New Year's sermon,

24
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
and he was looking back at the year that had just passed

25
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
and looking forward to the year to come.

26
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And so he decided to write a hymn to go along with his New Year's sermon.

27
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
He gave it the sensational, memorable title,

28
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Faith's Review and Expectation.

29
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
So to go along with the sermon, look back in the past to see what God had done,

30
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Faith's Review, and look forward in expectation of what God would do in the future.

31
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So have you heard Faith's Review and Expectation before that old hymn?

32
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:16.000
I mean, you may have.

33
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
It's now one of the most popular songs that has ever been written.

34
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
The Library of Congress has over 3,000 recordings of it on file.

35
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
It's been recorded well over 6,000 times,

36
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:35.000
and it's been performed millions of times, even in space on the backpipes.

37
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
And it begins this way, Faith's Review and Expectation.

38
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Amazing grace, how sweet the sound.

39
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
That saved a wretch like me.

40
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I once was lost, but now I'm found.

41
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Was blind, but now I see.

42
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Amazing grace as it's now known was deeply personal to John Newton,

43
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
not just for his sermon.

44
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
He was a man who knew that he had received God's grace

45
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
and had been transformed by it.

46
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
If you're not familiar with this story,

47
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
I'd encourage you to go grab a biography,

48
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
because he was, for example, he had been involved in the slave trade

49
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
and having been transformed by God's grace.

50
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
He was then an ally in the abolitionist movement.

51
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.000
He was against slavery.

52
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
His life had been transformed by grace.

53
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
What is it about that song, Amazing Grace,

54
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
that resonates with so many people?

55
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
You hear it sung not just in churches,

56
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
but in kind of non-religious contexts as well.

57
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
What is so amazing about grace?

58
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Well, our passage this morning shows us

59
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
and the whole message of Ephesians 2 verses 1-10

60
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
can really be summarized by a phrase that Paul repeats

61
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
in verse 5 and verse 8, and it is this,

62
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
By grace you have been saved.

63
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
By grace you have been saved.

64
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
So this morning we're going to simply look at

65
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
what it means to be saved by grace.

66
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And we're going to consider that by looking at

67
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
three or four kind of key concepts here.

68
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
We're going to look at salvation,

69
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
we're going to look at being saved.

70
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
We're going to look at then grace,

71
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
and we're going to look at faith,

72
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
and we're going to look at good works.

73
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
We're just going to walk through those together.

74
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So first of all, salvation.

75
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
By grace you have been saved.

76
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Salvation is one of those words that gets kind of thrown

77
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
around in Christian circles,

78
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
and there can be a lot of confusion.

79
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
You might hear about how many people got saved

80
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
at a particular church meeting,

81
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
or somebody might ask you if you have been saved.

82
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
What does it really mean to be saved?

83
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Well the word simply means to rescue.

84
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Inherent in the word saved or salvation

85
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.000
is being in a place of danger or peril or harm.

86
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
In the Bible you see it used in a couple of different ways.

87
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
One is you see it being used in reference to people

88
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
who are in physical need or physical danger.

89
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So Mark chapter 5, a diseased woman reaches out

90
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
and touches the hem of Jesus' garment,

91
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
and she's healed.

92
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And she said that she did that in order to be saved.

93
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And what she meant was that she was reaching out

94
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
in her need to be healed of her disease.

95
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
And the word she uses to describe that

96
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
is the same word here in Ephesians 2 for saved.

97
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
In Matthew chapter 14, you see Peter, the disciple,

98
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
walking on the water with Jesus.

99
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:30.000
It's a miracle.

100
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Of course Peter then looks at the wind in the waves.

101
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
He begins to sink and as he's sinking he cries out,

102
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Lord save me.

103
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:38.000
What is he saying there?

104
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
He's not saying, Lord take me to heaven when I drown.

105
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:43.000
He's not saying that.

106
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
He's saying I'm drowning please pull me out of this sea.

107
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
So that being said, yes,

108
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
refers to being saved from physical danger

109
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
but it also and most often so refers to our spiritual need.

110
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And that is what Paul is referring to here.

111
00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.000
So we need to see that spiritual danger is just as real

112
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:09.000
as any physical danger that we might face.

113
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Speaking of danger and kind of darker things,

114
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
I mean this past month it's been kind of normal

115
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
to decorate your yard with tombstones

116
00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
and other reminders of death and all the rest.

117
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And I understand that but also there are times

118
00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
when it has even kept people from seeing actual danger

119
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
that they were in.

120
00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:37.000
So I read a story about a haunted house attraction in Nashville

121
00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.000
where some teenagers were going around with some friends

122
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
and they were laughing having a great time

123
00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
and then one of them grabbed a prop which was a knife

124
00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
and they then proceeded to go for their friend with it

125
00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
only to find out afterwards that it wasn't just a prop.

126
00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
It was an actual real knife that had been used.

127
00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
Thankfully their friend survived.

128
00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
But when it comes to spiritual need and the danger we're in,

129
00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
we're not just dealing with a kind of representation.

130
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
Paul's not sort of giving us a prop here to give us an idea.

131
00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:12.000
He's talking about real danger that we are in.

132
00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And last Sunday Richard really helped us walking through

133
00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
the opening verses of Ephesians chapter 2

134
00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
showing us the terrifying reality of our spiritual condition

135
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:27.000
without Christ at the start of the chapter.

136
00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
And I'm not going to revisit everything he said last week

137
00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
but we are, if we're going to understand salvation

138
00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.000
we need to see the desperate situation that we are in.

139
00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So Paul's talking about salvation because of what he said earlier.

140
00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
So why do we need to be saved or rescued?

141
00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
What is the specific danger?

142
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
We need to be saved because of, to remind us,

143
00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
we need to be saved because of who we were.

144
00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So it says at the start, verse 1, and then he repeats it in verse 5,

145
00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.000
you were dead in your trespasses and sins.

146
00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
In chapter 2 and verse 3 he says,

147
00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:10.000
you were by nature, children of wrath like the rest of mankind.

148
00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:15.000
In other words, our fallenness goes right to the core of who we are.

149
00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
We are sinners by nature and this is true of, it says,

150
00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
all of mankind.

151
00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
This is true ever since the fall of man in the garden.

152
00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
You can go back to Genesis chapter 3 or read about that in Romans chapter 5.

153
00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
We are all sinners by nature.

154
00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And this is described here as death.

155
00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
It isn't merely pointing to the fact that we're just going to die one day physically.

156
00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
It tells us that even while we were alive physically,

157
00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.000
we were already dead spiritually when we came into this world.

158
00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
You see, our sin separates us from God and if you are separated from God,

159
00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
you are cut off from the very source of life.

160
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
So we need to be saved because of who we are by nature.

161
00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
We also need to be saved because of what we did.

162
00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:11.000
We who were by nature sinners then sinned.

163
00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:17.000
In other words, our behavior showed our sin nature.

164
00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.000
So you don't have to teach a person to sin anymore and you've got to teach a dog to bark.

165
00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.000
It comes out naturally.

166
00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
So our sin comes out how?

167
00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:34.000
We saw it in that we live according to our own sinful desires that spoke about.

168
00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
We live according to the pattern of this world.

169
00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
We live according to the power of spiritual darkness.

170
00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.000
So we were so entrenched in this way of life that we cannot break free from it any more

171
00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:51.000
than someone who is dead can break free from coffin.

172
00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And that's the reality of our condition without Christ.

173
00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So what's that mean for us?

174
00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
Some view Christianity as a way to maybe enrich their life

175
00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
or to make a few improvements here and there.

176
00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
They might think, well, I mean, generally speaking,

177
00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
I'm a pretty good person and of course I need a little forgiveness here and there

178
00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
and a help to improve my life.

179
00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And so Christianity comes in to kind of help you make some improvements.

180
00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
But the problem we see here goes far deeper than that.

181
00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Paul doesn't like take us to a beauty shop to make a few improvements

182
00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
or to give us a makeover.

183
00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
He takes us to the morgue and he says,

184
00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:36.000
this is how dire your natural spiritual condition is.

185
00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Fact is you can make all the kind of religious external improvements you want,

186
00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:45.000
but then that cannot change the spiritual condition that you are in.

187
00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
This radical problem requires a radical solution.

188
00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
If you're dead, the only solution that we'll do is resurrection.

189
00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And the good news is that God raises the dead.

190
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And this is the salvation he provides.

191
00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
He gives us new life.

192
00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So how does he do it?

193
00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Let's move on to the second word then.

194
00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.000
So we're saved.

195
00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
So it tells us about the spiritual danger that we're in and God rescues us from that.

196
00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
And he does it by grace.

197
00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So grace is a favorite word of the apostle Paul.

198
00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.000
He uses it some 86 times in the New Testament.

199
00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.000
So what does it mean?

200
00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Well, most commonly it's defined as unmerited favor.

201
00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
And that's absolutely right.

202
00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
In verse five, we see that God is rich in mercy.

203
00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
So we might compare it to mercy.

204
00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
So mercy is God not giving us what we do deserve,

205
00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.000
withholding His wrath, and grace is God giving us freely what we do not deserve.

206
00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
He freely gives us the gift of salvation.

207
00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.000
It's his unmerited favor.

208
00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
But like our sinful actions flow from our sinful nature,

209
00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
so his gracious actions, his kindness towards us,

210
00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
flows from his gracious nature.

211
00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
This is speaking of who God is and what he does when it speaks of grace here.

212
00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
So grace is about who God is.

213
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So God is gracious by his very nature,

214
00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
and he cannot be any more or any less gracious than he already is.

215
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:25.000
So 1 Peter chapter five and verse 10 refers to God as the God of all grace.

216
00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
You see it pointing us to God himself in the text.

217
00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
I mean, the whole thing hinges on those two words, but God.

218
00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So we were dead in our sin, but God steps in to save us by His grace.

219
00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So grace is, we might say, the disposition of God's heart

220
00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:54.000
that inclines him to pour out his kindness upon us, freely giving us salvation.

221
00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
But notice how gracious he is here.

222
00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
You know, is he frugal with his grace?

223
00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Does he kind of carefully comb over his monitored budget

224
00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
to see how much he can spare this month?

225
00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
No, Paul speaks about his immeasurable grace,

226
00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
the immeasurable riches of his grace.

227
00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So God is rich not only in the sense that he ultimately owns everything,

228
00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
he's rich in terms of his gracious character

229
00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and his utter willingness to freely give again and again.

230
00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:32.000
He gladly lavishes his grace upon us.

231
00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
And no matter how much grace he shows, there's more where it came from.

232
00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And in fact, in fact, you see in chapter two and verse seven,

233
00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
it will take all of eternity for him to put his grace on display

234
00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:49.000
and his continual kindness towards us as his people.

235
00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
So grace is about who God is by nature, but it's also about what he gives.

236
00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
So his character is seen in his actions.

237
00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And salvation here is the specific gift of grace that Paul is emphasizing here.

238
00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
So let's return to what kind of salvation we need.

239
00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
If we're dead, we need new life.

240
00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.000
So how does God graciously give us new life?

241
00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
The answer is in Christ.

242
00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:21.000
So a few weeks ago, in the kind of very first talk based on Ephesians chapter one

243
00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
verses kind of one to two, we looked at our identity in Christ

244
00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
and Paul is returning to that theme here really.

245
00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
So over and over, Paul talks about us being in Christ,

246
00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
about how our life is bound up in his, in other words.

247
00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So but here in this text, Paul speaks about it in a slightly different way.

248
00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Three times, notice in verses five and six,

249
00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
he speaks about us being together with Christ.

250
00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
You see it?

251
00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Verse five, he makes us alive together with Christ.

252
00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
He raised us up with him.

253
00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
He seats us with him in the heavenly places in Christ Jesus.

254
00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
So here's what God does by his grace.

255
00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:15.000
He unites us to Christ and he graciously causes us to participate

256
00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
in what happens to him.

257
00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
And we share with Christ in his death, in his resurrection,

258
00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:29.000
in his ascension, and we are now seated together with him in heavenly places.

259
00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
I don't know about you, but I enjoy watching a good helicopter rescue.

260
00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
You know, there's one that tends to happen once a year or so.

261
00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
I typed it in on YouTube this past week.

262
00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And there's so many that come up where somebody is say in a raging river

263
00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
and then the rescue crew comes in with a helicopter

264
00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
and it kind of repels down.

265
00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
And when they get to them in the river, they harness them to themselves.

266
00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.000
They kind of strap them in and then they get pulled right back up out of that raging river.

267
00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.000
And they go right up to where the helicopter is and they're pulled in

268
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
and maybe they then head off to a hospital where they land there

269
00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
and they're brought to safety.

270
00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
Why do I share that?

271
00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
I share that because you almost see like a similar movement in salvation here.

272
00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.000
So God comes down, if you will, in a rescue mission in the person of Jesus.

273
00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
Jesus descends into death.

274
00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
He rises again and ascends to his Father in heaven.

275
00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
You see that movement there?

276
00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:29.000
And like this kind of river rescue, if you will, he unites us to himself.

277
00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
He harnesses us to himself.

278
00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
We are united to him.

279
00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And so where he goes, we go.

280
00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
Right? So we died with him.

281
00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And God gives us new life with him.

282
00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And that life goes on forever with him.

283
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
That is how gracious God is.

284
00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
But let me draw your attention to verse nine.

285
00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.000
We're going to get into this a little bit more in a second.

286
00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.000
But when it speaks about God's grace there, in verse eight about it being the gift of God,

287
00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
it then talks about it not being a result of works so that no one may boast.

288
00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:11.000
So if it is by grace, therefore, it means it is not of works.

289
00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:17.000
If it was of works, we could boast in contributing to our salvation in some way.

290
00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:24.000
So all the glory goes to God because it is entirely of his grace that we are saved.

291
00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
So there's nothing.

292
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.000
No amount of religion, no amount of good works that can make us right with God.

293
00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And that's a very different message to literally every other religion in the world.

294
00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Religion says, do.

295
00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Grace says, it's done.

296
00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
Religion is about what we do to get to God.

297
00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:53.000
Grace is about what God did for us in Jesus when he came to save us.

298
00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:00.000
And that's perhaps easy to recognize when you're talking about an obviously non-Christian religion,

299
00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:06.000
but there are some slippery versions out there as well that would kind of take the name of Christian on,

300
00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.000
but preach a message of works rather than grace.

301
00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
So take Mormonism for example.

302
00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Now, don't miss hearing this.

303
00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:23.000
We've got some very dear Mormon friends for example, the best neighbors you could have asked for.

304
00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:30.000
But I do take issue with Mormonism and one of the reasons is this very issue.

305
00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:35.000
So I'll give you a verse from the Book of Mormon.

306
00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Second Nephi, chapter 25 verse 23.

307
00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Notice how it almost echoes what Paul says here in Ephesians 2, 8, 9.

308
00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.000
It says, for we know that it is by grace that we are saved after all that we can do.

309
00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
Do you see the difference?

310
00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
One says by grace you are saved, it is not of works.

311
00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:00.000
The other says by grace you are saved after all that you can do.

312
00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.000
The fact is here, it's clear, we cannot do anything to save ourselves.

313
00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:10.000
You can't give yourself a new life any more than a dead man can give himself new life.

314
00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:18.000
It isn't that we do our part, that we do the best we can and then God's grace makes up the rest.

315
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:26.000
The God who is immeasurably rich in grace isn't looking to kind of split the bill with us when it comes to salvation.

316
00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.000
He's already paid for it and he gives it to us freely.

317
00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:35.000
So salvation is not some reward that we achieve.

318
00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.000
It is a gift that we receive.

319
00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:44.000
So if you can't earn it, you might ask, well how can you know that you've received it?

320
00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:52.000
Okay, so salvation is entirely of grace. How can I know that I've received that gift of salvation?

321
00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
Ephesians 2 verse 8.

322
00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:04.000
It repeats that phrase by grace you have been saved, it was in verse 5, but then it adds the two words, through faith.

323
00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:09.000
So God's gift of salvation comes to us through faith.

324
00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:14.000
So Romans chapter 4 verse 5, one of many verses that speaks of this, but I'll read it as well.

325
00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
It says,

326
00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:21.000
And to the one who does not work but believes in him who justifies the ungodly,

327
00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:29.000
his faith is counted as righteousness. So we're saved through faith. So what is faith?

328
00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:34.000
But simply it is trusting in Jesus to save you.

329
00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
It's trusting in Christ.

330
00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:46.000
We don't trust in our good works, our church attendance, our giving, our helping, our neighbor, whatever it is.

331
00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:54.000
We don't trust in the sincerity of a decision we made years ago when we wrote the date in our Bible that we were told to,

332
00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:59.000
and we look back and like we put our trust in our decision itself.

333
00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:07.000
We put our trust in Christ himself, what he has done for us.

334
00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:15.000
So it is believing, yes, faith is believing, but it's more than just acknowledging that something is true intellectually.

335
00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:21.000
It is trusting in the grace of God to save you because of what Christ has done for you.

336
00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:29.000
It is entrusting yourself to the one who died and rose again to bring us to God.

337
00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:35.000
So have you put your faith in Jesus?

338
00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:41.000
Back in the 19th century there was a Trapeze artist by the name of Blondin.

339
00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.000
I'm sure that's not how you pronounce it.

340
00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:50.000
He was a French guy and he actually did some work near where we used to live in England doing his Trapeze work.

341
00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
Perhaps his most famous thing he ever did was go across Niagara Falls.

342
00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:01.000
So he went across Niagara Falls and the crowd was all there cheering him on as he walked across and came back.

343
00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Also he then got this wheelbarrow.

344
00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:08.000
He went across with a wheelbarrow and then he went to the crowd and he said,

345
00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:14.000
Who believes that I can take someone across in this wheelbarrow?

346
00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
Of course the crowd cheered.

347
00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:17.000
Yeah, you can do it.

348
00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And he said, OK, who's going to get in the wheelbarrow?

349
00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
And it was quiet.

350
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:32.000
You might say believed that he could do it, but were they willing to put their faith in him to actually trust in him?

351
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
Do you see the difference there?

352
00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And in the same way we can say, well, yeah, I believe that there was this man Jesus that he died for a sins, that he rose again.

353
00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
That's all true.

354
00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:47.000
But you know, the devil believes and he trembles.

355
00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
He's not saved.

356
00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:57.000
Faith is putting your trust personally in that one who died and rose again.

357
00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
It's getting into the wheelbarrow.

358
00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.000
It's entrusting yourself to him.

359
00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
But notice what else it says about faith.

360
00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.000
It is a gift of God.

361
00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:14.000
So when he says you've been saved by grace through faith, he then says, and this is not your own doing.

362
00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
It is the gift of God.

363
00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:25.000
And the it spoken of here refers really to the whole movement of salvation that you see happening in this passage.

364
00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
And that includes our faith in him.

365
00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:31.000
All of it is by grace.

366
00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:39.000
Both our salvation and the means by which we are saved.

367
00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:44.000
So like we said earlier, it isn't that we do our part and then God does his.

368
00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.000
So faith is the means by which we receive salvation.

369
00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Yes, but it isn't transactional.

370
00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:57.000
It isn't like, okay, I bring my faith to the table and God brings his grace to the table.

371
00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:02.000
Even the faith that receives salvation is a gift of grace.

372
00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.000
And we don't just see that here in Ephesians chapter two.

373
00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
You can see this in other places in scripture.

374
00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:15.000
So you look at Philippians chapter one in verse 29 speaks of faith as a gift from God.

375
00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:20.000
But I'm fascinated walking through the book of Acts seeing it play out in practice there in the early church.

376
00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:25.000
Like as Luke writes about people coming to faith in Christ, it's interesting what he writes.

377
00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.000
So take Acts chapter three and verse 16.

378
00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:32.000
He speaks about people putting their faith in Jesus.

379
00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.000
And in that same verse in the same breath, he talks about the faith that is through Jesus.

380
00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:42.000
So faith in Jesus is also faith through Jesus.

381
00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:43.000
Right?

382
00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
So it's in him and it's through him.

383
00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:50.000
The word faith isn't used in Acts chapter 16 verse 14.

384
00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:58.000
But it talks about how as Paul preaches the gospel in Philippi, a lady called Lydia responds to the message of the gospel.

385
00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
It's clear that she responds in faith.

386
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
But here's how it describes her response.

387
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:09.000
It says, the Lord opened Lydia's heart to pay attention to what was being said by Paul.

388
00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
So why was she listening?

389
00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:12.000
Why was she paying attention?

390
00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:17.000
Because the Lord opened her heart so that she would hear what he was saying.

391
00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:23.000
It talks about the Bible teacher Apollos in Acts chapter 18 verse 27.

392
00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.000
And it describes his ministry in this way.

393
00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:31.000
It talks about how he helped those who had believed through grace.

394
00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:33.000
So he was helping these believers.

395
00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
How did they believe through grace?

396
00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
We might say, well, what does that matter?

397
00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:45.000
Why are we making that kind of distinction here that both grace receives the gift and is in itself a gift?

398
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
Well, it matters for several reasons.

399
00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
Let me just give you a couple.

400
00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:53.000
One that I take great comfort in personally, it's not in the text.

401
00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:56.000
So this is just kind of me over here sharing something.

402
00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:03.000
I find it a great comfort that I can pray for someone's salvation, someone who does not know the Lord.

403
00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And I can pray with confidence that God is able to save them.

404
00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:14.000
I can pray that they would hear the message of the gospel, that they would believe in Christ.

405
00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.000
And know that God is able to give them the faith that he calls them to.

406
00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:20.000
So we can all do that.

407
00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:24.000
So let's pray that people would be saved that God would give that to them.

408
00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:32.000
But the reason that is given here in the text, once again, is what we might, or what Paul calls, boasting.

409
00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:37.000
So when it comes to our salvation, we have nothing to boast in.

410
00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Not even our faith in him.

411
00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
We boast in Jesus and in him alone.

412
00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
We boast in grace.

413
00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:51.000
We give God all the glory.

414
00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:52.000
All right.

415
00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:58.000
But to say that salvation is through faith alone, finally, is not to say that good works do not matter.

416
00:26:58.000 --> 00:26:59.000
They do.

417
00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.000
Now salvation, so let's think about good works together.

418
00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Salvation is not a result of our good works, but it does result in good works.

419
00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:17.000
So good works is not the root of our salvation, we might say, but it is the fruit of our salvation.

420
00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:23.000
Last week on Halloween Day, I had somebody come up to me and wished me a happy Reformation Day.

421
00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And what they were referring to is back on October 31st, 1517, the German reformer Martin Luther nailed his 95 thesis to a church door in Wittenberg.

422
00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
And that's kind of marked as the kind of start of the Protestant Reformation.

423
00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:48.000
And there were some major truths of Scripture that were there all along that were kind of recovered and preached once again.

424
00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:53.000
One of them being the salvation is by grace alone through faith alone.

425
00:27:53.000 --> 00:28:01.000
But we also see that the reformers did not downplay the importance of our works, that they clearly preached salvation through faith alone.

426
00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:05.000
So let me give you a quote from John Calvin, another reformer.

427
00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:15.000
He says, it is therefore faith alone which justifies and yet the faith which justifies is not alone.

428
00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:23.000
So that's kind of been paraphrased a number of times as the faith that is faith alone that saves but faith that saves is never alone.

429
00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
So what is meant by that there?

430
00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.000
So if we've been saved through faith, then that will be seen in the good works that follow.

431
00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:34.000
And you see that in verse 10, what does it say?

432
00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:40.000
It says, for we are his workmanship created in Christ Jesus.

433
00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
Why does he create us in Christ Jesus?

434
00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:52.000
It's revisiting what we've already seen that new life in Christ for good works which God prepared beforehand that we should walk in them.

435
00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:58.000
Now having just said everything I said, you could argue that we are saved by good works.

436
00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
It's just not our good works.

437
00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
It's his good works.

438
00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
We are his workmanship.

439
00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:18.000
So the God who formed Adam from the dust of the ground and breathed life in him created us anew in Christ Jesus.

440
00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Second Corinthians chapter 5 verse 17 says, therefore if anyone is in Christ, he has a new creation.

441
00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
If he has passed away behold the new has come.

442
00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
Alright so he's created us in Christ Jesus.

443
00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
Why did he create us?

444
00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:37.000
Well when God created man and placed him in the garden, what came next?

445
00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:42.000
Genesis chapter 2 and verse 15, he gave him work to do in the garden.

446
00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And that work was before the fall.

447
00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
In other words it was good.

448
00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.000
You see that flow happening there in the order of creation.

449
00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
The same thing is happening in new creation here.

450
00:29:52.000 --> 00:30:02.000
So we weren't made a new creation in Christ so that we could kind of sit around and say, well isn't that great?

451
00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:08.000
We were saved, made new in Christ that we might work.

452
00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:14.000
You see the life that we have in Christ is seen in the life that we then live for Christ.

453
00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:22.000
And those good works are laid out for us by the way specifically in detail in chapter 4, 5 and 6 of the text.

454
00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:25.000
So that's the kind of flow of Ephesians.

455
00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:28.000
Chapters 1 to 3 we see this is who we are in Christ.

456
00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:33.000
Chapters 4 to 6 this is what it means looks like to walk in him.

457
00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:37.000
And so there are good works that are general for every believer.

458
00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:40.000
But then there are also gifts that he's given to us individually.

459
00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And specific opportunities for good works.

460
00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:48.000
And he's prepared those for us to walk in as well.

461
00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:53.000
So just see here the chapters come full circle from verse 1 to verse 10.

462
00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:58.000
Before we were following after our sinful desires, following after the pattern of the world and the devil.

463
00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
And now we are following after Christ.

464
00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:06.000
We're living for him because of what he has done for us because we have been given this new life in him.

465
00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:11.000
The new life is seen in that growth that takes place, growth in his likeness.

466
00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:17.000
That doesn't mean we'll be perfect far from it but we can say with John Newton.

467
00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
I am not the man I ought to be.

468
00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
I am not the man I wish to be.

469
00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
I'm not the man I hope to be.

470
00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:32.000
But by the grace of God I am not the man I used to be by his grace I am who I am.

471
00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:39.000
A few years ago there's a guy who was cataloging music for a museum.

472
00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:44.000
And while he was kind of cataloging it, he noticed a file he hadn't seen before.

473
00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
It kind of dropped out.

474
00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.000
It was a piece of music.

475
00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:52.000
And on that piece of music had the name of the legendary composer.

476
00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:56.000
I'm a butcher, pronunciation Chopin.

477
00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.000
C-H-O-P-I-N.

478
00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:03.000
And as he pulled it out and he said, could that really be his?

479
00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
You could look it up on the BBC.

480
00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:09.000
He pulled it out and he walked over to a piano and sure enough he played it.

481
00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
And it was this beautiful piece of music.

482
00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:13.000
And that music had been sat there for years.

483
00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
And the first time it was played was fairly recently.

484
00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.000
I think it was like 2019.

485
00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
It was amazing.

486
00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:27.000
The good works that God has prepared for us were prepared beforehand.

487
00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:33.000
And now the call is for us to take them and to play them out, to walk in them.

488
00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:38.000
In fact, the word that he uses for workmanship here is poema.

489
00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:42.000
It's where we get our English word poem from.

490
00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
We could say that we are his poetry.

491
00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:49.000
But that word is used to refer to any kind of like work of art.

492
00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:53.000
So it isn't a stretch to say that God has created this piece of music

493
00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:56.000
and it is sounding out through our lives.

494
00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:02.000
And his workmanship is coming through as we who have been saved by his grace.

495
00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.000
Also live by his grace for his glory.

496
00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
And what does that music sound like?

497
00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:12.000
You might say it sounds like amazing grace.

498
00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:17.000
It looks like the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ.

499
00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.000
So let's pray now.

500
00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:28.000
Lord, we thank you so much for the amazing grace that you have shown us in Jesus.

501
00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:39.000
And so Lord, I pray that even if there's anyone here who has not received the gift of your salvation through Jesus.

502
00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:47.000
Lord, I pray that you would help them, enable them to come to you, to put their trust in Jesus.

503
00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:51.000
Receive the gift of salvation by faith.

504
00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:57.000
Lord, I pray that you would help us to live out of that grace.

505
00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:04.000
That we would not fall back into old patterns of depending on our own good works or following after our own desires.

506
00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Lord, I pray that you would fill us with so much gratitude for what you have done for us in Jesus that we would long to live for him.

507
00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Lord, we thank you that the life that is lived for him is the life that is lived by him.

508
00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:25.000
So I pray that you would help us by your grace to live as your workmanship in the world.

509
00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:30.000
So Lord, we pray that our lives would be lived by your grace and for your glory.

510
00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:33.000
In Jesus' name. Amen.

